{
  "texts": [
    "Large Language Models (LLMs) have demonstrated strong performance across various NLP benchmarks (Fourrier et al., 2024).",
    "Though LLMs have shown impressive generalization capabilities (for example, via In-context learning (Dong et al., 2024)), sometimes these tend to have lower performance on some niche or low-resource tasks, thus requiring task-specific fine-tuning.",
    "LLMs usage follows a pre-train and fine-tune paradigm (Zhao et al., 2023), where the model is trained on a massive amount of text in an unsupervised fashion, and subsequently, the model is fine-tuned for some specific tasks/domains in a supervised setting.",
    "Given the size of these models (order of billions of parameters), it may not always be feasible to fine-tune the entire model due to high computational costs.",
